PROMPT 63: What are WSDOT requirements for retaining wall drainage design?
======================================================================
RESPONSE:
- One of the principal causes of retaining wall/slope failure is the additional hydrostatic load imposed by an increase in the water content in the material behind the wall or slope. This condition results in a substantial increase in the hydrostatic pressure, which can lead to failure if not properly managed.
- Drainage design is critical to mitigate the risk of failure due to increased water content. The design must ensure that water is effectively drained from the backfill material to reduce hydrostatic pressure.
- Contact the HQ Geotechnical Office and HQ Hydraulics Office to determine whether a scour analysis is required at locations where a retaining wall or reinforced slope can bein contact with water.^^^1^^^- Free Draining Backfill to Extend at Least 12" Behind Wall (Crushed No. 57 per WSDOT 9-03.1(4)C)
